"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864320","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-22","<p>Apprenticeships (which incorporate paid work of at least 30 hours a week) are treated in the same way as other paid work for benefit purposes. When a person is in receipt of a benefit and they start employment as an apprentice, their entitlement to benefit may change in light of their new circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Regardless of their age and circumstances, claimants are not eligible for the main working age benefits, such as Income Support, Jobseeker’s Allowance or Employment and Support Allowance if they work 16 hours a week or more, on average. Additionally, claimants are not eligible for Income Support, income-based Jobseeker’s Allowance and or income-related Employment and Support Allowance if they have a partner who works 24 hours a week or more, on average.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit is being rolled out across the country and is replacing the main means tested benefits listed above. Earnings from an apprenticeship are treated in the same way as any other form of employed earnings and would be taken into account when calculating entitlement to Universal Credit, which is both an in-work and out-of-work benefit.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-03-22T17:27:40.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864320/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864320/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-15","Social Security Benefits: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which eligible benefits are (a) lost and (b) suspended when a young person aged between 16 and 24 becomes an apprentice.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","132804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864321","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-21","<p>The department does not hold the information, however for those granted leave to remain as a result of a successful asylum claim, a joint fast track NINo application process operates between DWP and the Home Office. From 15 January 2018 the process is applicable to the principal family member and any adult dependants aged 16 or over in the refugees family, with the NINo being allocated within 48 hours of receipt of the application.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-21T14:22:14.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864321/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864321/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-15","Asylum: National Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many asylum seekers who have indefinite leave to remain are awaiting the allocation of a national insurance number.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","132805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864322","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-20","<p>The Government is undertaking a wide range of analysis and preparatory work that will contribute to our exit negotiations with the EU, to define our future partnership with the EU, and to inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>It is not our usual practice to comment publicly on individual external publications, however we recognise the importance of contributions to the public debate.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>I would note that the analysis to which the Hon. Member refers considers the scenario in which we do not reach a deal with the EU. The Government is clear that we want our future relationship with the EU to be a deep and special partnership, taking in both economic and security cooperation. We are confident that this is in the interests of both sides, so we approach these negotiations anticipating success. We do not want or expect a no deal outcome.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2018-03-20T17:14:45.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864322/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864322/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-15","Brexit: Bureaucracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will make an assessment of the implications for the Government's policies of the Oliver Wyman report entitled The Red Tape Cost of Brexit, published on 12 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","132806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864323","Treasury","false","2018-03-20","<p>Automatic Enrolment has had great success in increasing participation rates in workplace pensions across the population. 9.4 million employees have been enrolled into workplace pensions since 2012. DWP’s figures show an increase of 44 percentage points in pension participation for those aged 22 to 29 from 2012 to 2016. Additionally, workplace pension participation among eligible men and women has equalised. We want to build on the increase in participation. The minimum contributions required under automatic enrolment will increase from the current 2% of qualifying earnings to 5% in April 2018 and 8% in April 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, in April 2017 the government also introduced the Lifetime ISA, allowing younger people to receive a 25% bonus from government on savings of up to £4,000 annually. This encourages the next generation to get into the habit of saving and helps them to simultaneously save for both a first house and for later life, with the same product.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-03-20T16:17:50.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864323/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864323/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-15","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to encourage people aged under 30 in employment to save towards their pensions.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","132807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864324","Treasury","false","2018-03-20","<p>The Government has a variety of policies that encourage self-employed retirement saving. Tax relief is provided on pension contributions, representing a significant incentive to save into a pension. As noted in DWP’s review of automatic enrolment in December, we are looking to build on the principles behind automatic enrolment’s success to help the self-employed save for retirement and DWP will be running tests of targeted interventions to help the self-employed save for retirement. As a first step, HM Treasury and DWP are co-hosting a ‘Tech Sprint’ event later this month with the ABI, working with industry and Fintech firms to develop innovative technology-based ideas to help the self-employed save for retirement.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-03-20T16:19:22.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864324/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864324/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-15","Pensions: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to encourage self-employed people to save towards their retirement.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","132808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864325","Treasury","false","2018-03-20","<p>We have increased the amount of money that people can save in their ISAs annually to a record £20,000 and introduced a Personal Savings Allowance of up to £1,000. Thanks to these measures over 95% of people pay no tax on their savings income. In April 2017 the government also introduced the Lifetime ISA, allowing younger people to receive a 25% bonus from government on savings of up to £4,000 annually. This encourages the next generation to get into the habit of saving and helps them to simultaneously save for both a first house and for later life, with the same product.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-03-20T16:20:21.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864325/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864325/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-15","Personal Savings","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what barriers to investing in savings by people aged under 30 his Department has identified.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","132809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864326","Home Office","false","2018-03-20","<p>The UK Immigration Rules have a comprehensive framework for refugees and their families to be safely reunited in the UK. Our family reunion policy allows immediate family members of those granted protection here to reunite with them. The Immigration Rules also provide for relatives with protection in the UK to sponsor children in serious and compelling circumstances. The Mandate resettlement scheme also allows those recognised by the UNCHR as refugees to join close family members here in the UK.</p><p>In addition, there is provision in the policy to grant visas outside the Rules in exceptional circumstances, which caters for extended family members who otherwise do not qualify under the Rules.</p><p>We do not believe there are unnecessary barriers to family reunion for refugees. Over the last five years there have been 24,700 family reunion visas issued –and this is in addition to the numbers granted asylum here or resettled here under our resettlement schemes.</p><p>We are listening carefully to concerns raised on this issue by Non-Governmental Organisations and others, we are currently reviewing our approach to family reunion as part of the Government’s wider asylum and resettlement policy.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-20T12:22:14.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864326/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864326/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-15","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of refugees residing in the UK who have been separated from their family due to not being eligible for family reunification.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","132810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864327","Department for Education","false","2018-03-23","<p>This information is in the public domain. We publish the number and proportion of pupils with special educational needs, including those who are also eligible for and claiming free school meals in England in the annual ‘Special educational needs in England’ statistical release which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen</a>.</p><p>We publish results from the Children in Need census in the annual ‘Characteristics of children in need’ statistical release which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-children-in-need#characteristics-of-children-in-need" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-children-in-need#characteristics-of-children-in-need</a>.</p><p>The number and proportion of children in need who have special educational needs are included in the Outcomes Tables, which were first published in 2012. We will publish the latest figures for 2017 on 28 March 2018.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","132812","2018-03-23T14:58:44.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864327/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864327/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-15","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate his Department has made of the number of young people who have been identified as having special educational needs or disability were (a) eligible for free school meals and (b) included in the Children in Need census in each of the last 10 years.","true","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","132811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864328","Department for Education","false","2018-03-23","<p>This information is in the public domain. We publish the number and proportion of pupils with special educational needs, including those who are also eligible for and claiming free school meals in England in the annual ‘Special educational needs in England’ statistical release which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen</a>.</p><p>We publish results from the Children in Need census in the annual ‘Characteristics of children in need’ statistical release which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-children-in-need#characteristics-of-children-in-need" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-children-in-need#characteristics-of-children-in-need</a>.</p><p>The number and proportion of children in need who have special educational needs are included in the Outcomes Tables, which were first published in 2012. We will publish the latest figures for 2017 on 28 March 2018.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","132811","2018-03-23T14:58:44.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864328/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864328/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-15","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, What the average proportion of children in mainstream education who were diagnosed with special educational needs or disability was in each year between 2010 and 2017.","true","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","132812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864329","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-23","<p>We have no current plans to amend the list of long-term and orphan diseases which qualify for free prescriptions. The last consultation on this issue was as part of Professor Sir Ian Gilmore’s review in 2008, which included consultation with patients, the public and general practitioners.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-23T14:18:42.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864329/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864329/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-15","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he plans to amend the list of long-term and orphan diseases which qualify for free prescriptions; and when he last consulted (a) patients, (b) doctors and (c) those in the (i) pharmaceutical and (ii) health industries on that subject.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","132813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864330","Treasury","false","2018-03-20","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer given by the Minister for Energy and Clean Growth (Claire Perry) on 15 March 2018 to PQ 131965.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-03-20T15:05:33.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864330/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864330/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-15","Energy: Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of business rate rises for onsite battery storage on the development of the UK battery storage market.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","132814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864331","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-23","<p>Primary Care Support England services are provided by Capita Business Services Ltd under contract with NHS England. The contract contains service standards, including Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) that specify the agreed measurement and evaluation of performance delivery. The KPIs relating to patient registration, medical records, local performers list, local medical committee, pensions and general practitioner payments are attached.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England closely monitors delivery of the services against these performance standards, which are reported by Capita on a monthly basis. However, information relating to targets and complaints is commercially sensitive and therefore we are unable to provide this information.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","132816 ; 132817 ; 132818 ; 132819 ; 132820","2018-03-23T14:40:55.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864331/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864331/answer","PCSE KPI List.docx","PQ132815 attached document","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/864331/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-15","Primary Care Support England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, which Key Performance Indicators (KPI) apply to the patients registration area of work carried out by Primary Care Support England (PCSE); how often PCSE reported against those KPIs; which targets were reached and how many complaints were received on those targets in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","132815"
